{"id":"1908.11862","submitter":"Carlos S\\'anchez Mu\\~noz","authors":"Carlos S\\'anchez Mu\\~noz, Berislav Buca, Joseph Tindall, Alejandro\n  Gonz\\'alez-Tudela, Dieter Jaksch, Diego Porras","title":"Symmetries and Conservation Laws in Quantum Trajectories: Dissipative\n  Freezing","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 100, 042113 (2019)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.100.042113","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.quant-gas cond-mat.stat-mech","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In driven-dissipative systems, the presence of a strong symmetry guarantees\nthe existence of several steady states belonging to different symmetry sectors.\nHere we show that, when a system with a strong symmetry is initialized in a\nquantum superposition involving several of these sectors, each individual\nstochastic trajectory will randomly select a single one of them and remain\nthere for the rest of the evolution. Since a strong symmetry implies a\nconservation law for the corresponding symmetry operator on the ensemble level,\nthis selection of a single sector from an initial superposition entails a\nbreakdown of this conservation law at the level of individual realizations.\nGiven that such a superposition is impossible in a classical, stochastic\ntrajectory, this is a a purely quantum effect with no classical analogue. Our\nresults show that a system with a closed Liouvillian gap may exhibit, when\nmonitored over a single run of an experiment, a behaviour completely opposite\nto the usual notion of dynamical phase coexistence and intermittency, which are\ntypically considered hallmarks of a dissipative phase transition. We discuss\nour results with a simple, realistic model of squeezed superradiance.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 30 Aug 2019 17:45:05 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-23"}
